import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

np.random.seed(0)
x = np.random.normal(0, 1, 100)
y = np.random.normal(2, 5, 100)
plt.scatter(x, y)
plt.xlabel('x')
plt.ylabel('y')
plt.show()

t = np.linspace(-np.pi, np.pi, 100)
sint = np.sin(t)
cost = np.cos(t)
plt.plot(t, sint, label='f(t)=sin(t)')
plt.plot(t, cost, label='f(t)=cos(t)')
plt.xlabel('t')
plt.ylabel('f(t)')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

np.random.seed(0)
xx = np.random.normal(0, 1, (100, 100))
plt.imshow(xx)
plt.xlabel('x')
plt.ylabel('y')
plt.show()

  • Create a line plot of the function y = x^2 from 0 to 10 with axis labels.
x = np.linspace(0, 10, 100)
y = x**2
plt.plot(x, y)
plt.xlabel('x')
plt.ylabel('y')
plt.show()

  • Create a scatter plot of 50 random 2D points with different colors and sizes.
x = np.random.normal(size=50)
y = np.random.normal(size=50)
colors = np.random.rand(50)
sizes = np.random.rand(50) * 100
plt.scatter(x, y, c=colors, s=sizes)
plt.show()

  • Create a bar chart of the number of apples, oranges, and bananas sold in a week.
fruits = ['Apples', 'Oranges', 'Bananas']
sales = [10, 8, 15]
plt.bar(fruits, sales)
plt.xlabel('Fruit')
plt.ylabel('Number of Sales')
plt.show()

  • Create a pie chart of the percentage of time spent on different activities in a day.
activities = ['Sleep', 'Work', 'Study', 'Exercise', 'Leisure']
times = [8, 8, 4, 1, 3]
plt.pie(times, labels=activities, autopct='%1.1f%%')

  • Create a histogram of 1000 normally distributed random numbers with 10 bins.
data = np.random.normal(size=1000)
plt.hist(data, bins=10)
plt.xlabel('Value')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.show()

  • Create a line plot of the sine and cosine functions from 0 to 2\(\pi\) with a legend and axis labels.
x = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, 100)
y1 = np.sin(x)
y2 = np.cos(x)
plt.plot(x, y1, label='sin(x)')
plt.plot(x, y2, label='cos(x)')
plt.xlabel('x')
plt.ylabel('y')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

  • Create a scatter plot of 1000 random 2D points with different colors and sizes based on their distance from the origin.
x = np.random.normal(size=1000)
y = np.random.normal(size=1000)
distance = np.sqrt(x**2 + y**2)
colors = distance
sizes = distance * 50
plt.scatter(x, y, c=colors, s=sizes, cmap='coolwarm')
plt.colorbar()
## <matplotlib.colorbar.Colorbar object at 0x147620190>
plt.show()

  • Create a stacked bar plot of the number of gold, silver, and bronze medals won by the top 5 countries in the 2016 Summer Olympics.
countries = ['USA', 'GBR', 'CHN', 'RUS', 'GER']
gold = [46, 27, 26, 19, 17]
silver = [37, 23, 18, 18, 10]
bronze = [38, 17, 26, 19, 15]
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.bar(countries, gold, label='Gold')
ax.bar(countries, silver, bottom=gold, label='Silver')
ax.bar(countries, bronze, bottom=np.array(gold)+np.array(silver), label='Bronze')
ax.set_xlabel('Country')
ax.set_ylabel('Medals')
ax.legend()
plt.show()

  • Create a heatmap of the correlation matrix between 5 variables with annotated values and axis labels.
np.random.seed(42)
data = np.random.normal(size=(5, 100))
corr = np.corrcoef(data)
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
im = ax.imshow(corr, cmap='coolwarm')
cbar = ax.figure.colorbar(im, ax=ax)
for i in range(5):
    for j in range(5):
        text = ax.text(j, i, f'{corr[i,j]:.2f}', ha='center', va='center', color='black')
ax.set_xticks(np.arange(5))
ax.set_yticks(np.arange(5))
ax.set_xticklabels(['Var 1', 'Var 2', 'Var 3', 'Var 4', 'Var 5'])
ax.set_yticklabels(['Var 1', 'Var 2', 'Var 3', 'Var 4', 'Var 5'])
plt.show()
